[Learning Phase]

🔹 Pattern 1: Left–Right Pointer
👉 Used when working on arrays/strings, usually sorted, or when shrinking a window from both sides.
📘 Beginner
LC 125 – Valid Palindrome 
LC 344 – Reverse String
LC 977 – Squares of a Sorted Array
LC 167 – Two Sum II (Input Array Is Sorted)

📘 Medium
LC 11 – Container With Most Water
LC 15 – 3Sum
LC 18 – 4Sum
LC 16 – 3Sum Closest
📌 Key Learning
One pointer starts from left, one from right
Move pointers based on condition (sum, comparison, mismatch)
Eliminates O(n²) brute force in many cases





🔹 Pattern 2: Fast–Slow Pointer
👉 Used when one pointer moves faster than the other Very common in arrays and linked lists
📘 Beginner
LC 141 – Linked List Cycle
LC 876 – Middle of the Linked List
LC 202 – Happy Number

📘 Medium
LC 287 – Find the Duplicate Number
LC 142 – Linked List Cycle II
📌 Key Learning
Fast moves 2x, slow moves 1x
If they meet → cycle exists
Helps reduce extra space (no HashSet)




🔹 Pattern 3: Opposite Ends (Special Case of Two Pointers)
👉 Pointers start from both ends, mostly in sorted arrays
📘 Beginner
LC 26 – Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array
LC 27 – Remove Element
LC 283 – Move Zeroes

📘 Medium
LC 80 – Remove Duplicates from Sorted Array II
LC 75 – Sort Colors
📌 Key Learning
One pointer tracks position
Other scans array
In-place operations (no extra space)


